article.headline: Wyoming 92, Washington 76
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- The start of the Washington-Wyoming game was delayed 15 minutes because of a malfunctioning clock, and when action resumed, Washington's offense also went haywire. Wyoming jumped up 7-0 on its way to a 38-point lead before settling for a 92-76 win Saturday. The Huskies missed their first 11 shots and fell behind 61-23 before a furious second-half rally made the final score respectable. For the first 6 minutes, time was kept with a stopwatch at the scorer's table and everyone else was in the dark about how many minutes remained. "I told the guy keeping the clock, if we're behind, stop it," joked Wyoming coach Steve McClain. Sparking the Cowboys was Jay Straight, who scored 18 points, grabbed six rebounds and sank six free throws in a row down the stretch to blunt the Huskies' comeback. Dion Sherrell and Mory Correa added 16 points each for Wyoming (3-2) while Joe Ries had 10. Washington (3-2) was led by Curtis Allen's 18 points off the bench, on six 3-pointers, while Bobby Jones had 14 and Will Conroy 12. McClain said he wasn't concerned the Cowboys' lead shrunk from 38 points with 17 minutes left to 11 with 5:32 to play. "That's the nice thing about being up by 30. They can rally all they want," he said. The Huskies fell behind 7-0, 28-6, 46-13 and 49-19 by halftime. "We just buried ourselves in such a hole the first half, it was too much to overcome," Washington coach Lorenzo Romar said. "Shots weren't dropping ... Their bigs were big and were bothering us when we went inside early, and defensively we just didn't play the type of defense we needed." After the Huskies closed within 80-69 on Allen's sixth 3-pointer, Straight hit two free throws and Correa stole the ball from Allen to set up a layup by Ries. After an air ball by Conroy, Straight sank two more foul shots and the Cowboys were comfortably up 86-69 with 4:16 left. Romar said the delay at the start was not a factor. "They had the same wait," he said. The Huskies had only three offensive rebounds in the first half, leading to numerous fast-break points on the Wyoming end. "The crowd was into it. They got easy buckets. We didn't defend like we're capable of defending," Allen said. "Hopefully this will be a learning experience for us." Of the failed comeback, Jones said, "We should have had that kind of fire at the beginning of the game instead of waiting until we were down by 30 points." The Cowboys, outrebounded by 22 in an 80-67 loss at Kansas State on Wednesday, turned the tables on Washington by a 52-30 margin. Ries had a game-high 11 boards. "Wednesday night was brutal," he said. "I could taste that in my mouth. That was bad. I was ticked off that we played that way. We just had to come out on fire tonight, and the guys did. Guys played hard and with energy and enthusiasm." Correa, who sank 7-of-8 field goals, had six blocked shots and five rebounds, said the Cowboys were embarrassed by their rebounding against K-State. "That's what we did all practice, just work on boxing out and we just came out hard and played defense," he said. McClain was proud of his team's hustle. "Early in the game, every loose ball, every rebound was ours," he said. "A lot of them were by our guards, and that's even better because then you've got the ball in a guard's hand and he can immediately push it, and we did a great job of being unselfish." Correa put the Cowboys up 61-23 on a reverse layup with 17:18 remaining. The Huskies slapped on a full-court press and fought to within 13 over a 10-minute stretch. Brandon Roy's steal and layin with 6:56 remaining cut the lead to 77-64. Allen hit 5-of-7 3-pointers in six-and-a-half minutes as the Huskies whittled the margin to 80-69 with 5:32 left. However, the Cowboys made all eight of their free throws down the stretch, Ries hit a layup and Correa had a dunk to secure the win. Sherrell scored 10 points in the first half as Wyoming blitzed to a 49-19 lead. Washington missed its first 11 shots and fell behind 7-0 before Anthony Washington's dunk at the 14:02 mark of the opening half. The Huskies had gone 15 minutes without a basket in their previous game, an 86-62 loss to No. 17 Gonzaga. Wyoming finished at 51 percent, while Washington made 42 percent of its shots.
